'''Leroy Aziz Sané''' ({{IPA|de|ˈliːʁɔʏ zaˈneː}};<ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oGfF3EN0g74&t=16s&ab_channel=FCBayernM%C3%BCnchen |title=Copy the Penalty Challenge {{!}} FC Bayern Summer Games 2022 {{!}} Episode 1 |date=10 June 2022 |publisher=FC Bayern München |access-date=30 March 2025 |via=YouTube}}</ref> born 11 January 1996) is a German professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Winger (association football)|winger]] for [[Süper Lig]] club [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] and the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]].

Sané made his professional debut for [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] in 2014 and transferred to [[Premier League]] club [[Manchester City]] in 2016 for an initial £37 million fee. He was voted [[PFA Young Player of the Year]] in 2017–18, becoming the first and so far only German player to win the award, after helping City win the league and [[EFL Cup]]. In 2020, he joined [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] on a five-year deal for an initial €45 million fee.

Sané made his senior international debut for Germany in November 2015 and was part of their squad that reached the semi-finals of [[UEFA Euro 2016]].

==Early life==
Sané was born on 11 January 1996 in [[Essen]] and was raised near the [[Lohrheidestadion]], [[Wattenscheid]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Philipp Rentsch|date=26 May 2015|title=Leroy Sane: Nicht einfach zwischen den Welten zu switchen|url=http://www.westline.de/fussball/schalke04/Leroy-Sane-Nicht-einfach-zwischen-den-Welten-zu-switchen%3Bart2009,2278266|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921082238/http://www.westline.de/fussball/schalke04/Leroy-Sane-Nicht-einfach-zwischen-den-Welten-zu-switchen;art2009,2278266|archive-date=21 September 2015|access-date=26 August 2015|work=westline|publisher=westline GbR: Aschendorff Medien GmbH & Co. KG und WestOnline GmbH & Co. KG in Gesellschaft bürgerlichen Rechts|language=de}}</ref> He is the son of former German [[Rhythmic gymnastics|rhythmic gymnast]] and [[1984 Summer Olympics]] bronze medalist [[Regina Weber]], and former footballer and [[Senegal national football team|Senegalese international]] [[Souleymane Sané]].<ref name="Sane commits to Schalke" /><ref>{{cite web|author=Zocher, Thomas|date=25 March 2014|title=Schalke reward academy star Leroy Sane with two-year deal|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11887/9231944/transfer-news-schalke-reward-academy-star-leroy-sane-with-two-year-deal|access-date=26 April 2014|website=Sky Sports|archive-date=6 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201006045716/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11887/9231944/transfer-news-schalke-reward-academy-star-leroy-sane-with-two-year-deal|url-status=live}}</ref> He was named Leroy in honour of [[Claude Le Roy]], a former head coach of his father.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Allemagne : Leroy Sané (Schalke 04) aurait-il pu jouer pour l'équipe de France ? |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Allemagne-leroy-sane-schalke-04-aurait-il-pu-jouer-pour-l-equipe-de-france/606705 |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=L'Équipe |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Senkrechtstarter Leroy Sané: Eine Chance in der deutschen Nationalmannschaft |url=https://www.eurosport.de/fussball/testspiel/2015/leroy-sane-eine-chance-fur-den-senkrechtstarter_sto4986250/story.shtml |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=www.eurosport.de}}</ref> His father met his mother while playing professionally for [[SG Wattenscheid 09]]. Souleymane Sané was raised in France; he moved to Germany through his service in the [[French Army]]. Sané's two brothers, Kim and [[Sidi Sané|Sidi]], have played for the youth side or second XI of major German football clubs.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sidi Sane: Leroy Sane's kid brother to train with Schalke first team |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/sidi-sane-leroy-sane-s-kid-brother-to-train-with-schalke-first-team-20286 |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=www.bundesliga.com |language=en}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Sané began playing football in 2001 for the youth team of SG Wattenscheid 09.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |date=2020-07-04 |title=7 things you may not know about Leroy Sané |url=https://bulinews.com/news/2428/7-things-know-leroy-sane |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=Bundesliga News in English |language=en}}</ref> In 2005, he joined [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]].<ref name=":2" /> Three years later, he joined [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]], before returning to the Schalke youth academy (''Nachwuchsleistungszentrum'') in 2011.<ref name=":2" />

===Schalke 04===
[[File:Leroy Sane MSV-Schalke-5932.jpg|thumb|Sané with [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] in 2015]]

On 21 March 2014, Sané signed a three-year professional contract with Schalke ending on 30 June 2017.<ref name="Sane commits to Schalke">{{cite web |url=http://www.schalke04.de/en/news/140321_sane/page/827--86--.html |title=Sane commits to Schalke |publisher=FC Schalke 04 |date=21 March 2014 |access-date=27 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903081117/http://www.schalke04.de/en/news/140321_sane/page/827--86--.html |archive-date=3 September 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He made his [[Bundesliga]] debut on 20 April 2014 against [[VfB Stuttgart]].<ref name="VfB Stuttgart vs. Schalke 04 at Soccerway"/> He replaced [[Max Meyer (footballer)|Max Meyer]] after 77 minutes in a 3–1 away defeat.<ref name="VfB Stuttgart vs. Schalke 04 at Soccerway">{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2014/04/20/germany/bundesliga/vfb-stuttgart-1893-ev/fc-schalke-04/1487295/ |title=Stuttgart vs. Schalke 04 3 – 1 |publisher=Soccerway |date=20 April 2014 |access-date=5 August 2015 |archive-date=10 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201010152230/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2014/04/20/germany/bundesliga/vfb-stuttgart-1893-ev/fc-schalke-04/1487295/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He scored his first goal of the [[2014–15 FC Schalke 04 season|season]] in a 2–1 home defeat to [[1. FC Köln]] on 13 December.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/blmd12v-ten-things-about-leroy-sane-fc-schalke-04.jsp |title=Ten things about Leroy Sané |publisher=Bundesliga |access-date=17 August 2018 |archive-date=17 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817193321/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/blmd12v-ten-things-about-leroy-sane-fc-schalke-04.jsp |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 11 March 2015, Sané scored in his first [[UEFA Champions League]] match in a 4–3 victory over [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]], although his side were knocked out of the [[2014–15 UEFA Champions League|competition]] on 5–4 aggregate.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lowe |first=Sid |date=2015-03-10 |title=Real Madrid made to sweat by never-say-die Schalke but shock averted |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/mar/10/real-madrid-schalke-champions-league-match-report |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2015-03-09 |title=Real Madrid 3-4 Schalke (5-4 agg) |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/31802502 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

===Manchester City===
====2016–17: Debut season====
On 2 August 2016, Sané joined [[Premier League]] club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]],<ref name="espn.co.uk">{{Cite web |date=2016-08-02 |title=Man City sign Sane from Schalke for £37m |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/37482264/manchester-city-complete-signing-leroy-sane-schalke |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref> signing a five-year contract for a reported £37&nbsp;million transfer fee, with performance-related add-ons potentially making the fee £46.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2016-08-02 |title=Leroy Sane: Germany midfielder joins Man City in £37m deal |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36950347 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name="espn.co.uk"/> He made his debut in a 1–2 win in the [[Manchester derby]] against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] on 10 September.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Taylor |first=Daniel |date=2016-09-10 |title=Manchester City's derby delight as De Bruyne inspires win over United |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/sep/10/manchester-united-manchester-city-premier-league-match-report |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=The Observer |language=en-GB |issn=0029-7712}}</ref> His first goal for City came in a 2–1 home win against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the Premier League on 18 December.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2016-12-16 |title=Manchester City 2-1 Arsenal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38279282 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Following a spell on the sidelines due to injury, Sané made his return in a game against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and scored in the 2–2 draw at the [[City of Manchester Stadium]] on 21 January 2017.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-01-20 |title=Manchester City 2-2 Tottenham Hotspur |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38620041 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 28 January, he scored in a 3–0 away win over Crystal Palace in the [[2016–17 FA Cup|FA Cup]] [[2016–17 FA Cup#Fourth round proper|fourth round]] match.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-01-27 |title=Crystal Palace 0-3 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/38700695 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 21 February, Sané scored in a 5–3 comeback win over [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] in the [[2016–17 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] [[2016–17 UEFA Champions League knockout phase#Manchester City v Monaco|round of 16]] first leg match.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-02-20 |title=Manchester City 5-3 Monaco |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39030973 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 1 March, he scored in a 5–1 home win over Huddersfield Town in the FA Cup [[2016–17 FA Cup#Fifth round proper|fifth round]] replay match.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-02-28 |title=Manchester City 5-1 Huddersfield Town |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39035253 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Four days later, on 5 March, he scored in a 2–0 away win over Sunderland.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Premier League: Sunderland v Man City |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/38604372 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 15 March, Sané scored in the [[2016–17 UEFA Champions League knockout phase#Monaco v Manchester City|return fixture]] of the Champions League tie against Monaco; however, City lost 1–3, knocking them out from the tournament on [[away goals rule|away goals]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-03-14 |title=Monaco 3-1 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39248906 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 2 April, Sané scored the opening goal in an eventual 2–2 draw with Arsenal.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-03-31 |title=Arsenal 2-2 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39396482 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 15 April, he scored in a 3–0 win over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-04-14 |title=Southampton 0-3 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39536675 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

In July 2017, Sané said he believed his debut season at City had been limited by his inability to breathe through his nose.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |date=23 May 2017 |title=Nose surgery rules Manchester City and Germany winger Leroy Sane out of 2017 Confederations Cup |url=https://talksport.com/football/nose-surgery-rules-manchester-city-and-germany-winger-leroy-sane-out-2017-confederations |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507095001/http://talksport.com/football/nose-surgery-rules-manchester-city-and-germany-winger-leroy-sane-out-2017-confederations |archive-date=7 May 2018 |access-date=5 February 2018 |work=talkSPORT}}</ref> He said he particularly suffered during matches, with his constantly blocked nose hampering his performance and causing him intense frustration.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/leroy-sane-manchester-city-nose-10875407 |title=Leroy Sane gets a nose job as he looks to get Man City career back on track |agency=Press Association |date=26 July 2017 |work=mirror |access-date=5 February 2018 |archive-date=23 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201123034124/https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/leroy-sane-manchester-city-nose-10875407 |url-status=live }}</ref> He opted to have corrective surgery during the off-season break. Although this caused him to miss that year's [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup|FIFA Confederations Cup]], he said his chronic nasal congestion was becoming increasingly unbearable for him and that he wished to enter the next season feeling happy and healthy.<ref>{{Cite news |last=talkSPORT |date=2017-05-23 |title=Nose surgery rules Manchester City and Germany winger Leroy Sane out of 2017 Confederations Cup |url=https://talksport.com/football/nose-surgery-rules-manchester-city-and-germany-winger-leroy-sane-out-2017-confederations |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507095001/http://talksport.com/football/nose-surgery-rules-manchester-city-and-germany-winger-leroy-sane-out-2017-confederations |archive-date=7 May 2018 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=talkSPORT |language=en |url-status=dead }}</ref>

====2017–19: Back-to-back league titles====
[[File:Leroy Sané in December 2017 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Sané with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2017]]
Sané scored his first two goals of the [[2017–18 Manchester City F.C. season|2017–18 season]] in City's 5–0 home win against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 9 September 2017.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Taylor |first=Daniel |date=2017-09-09 |title=Manchester City and Gabriel Jesus hammer 10-man Liverpool 5-0 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/sep/09/manchester-city-liverpool-premier-league-match-report |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=The Observer |language=en-GB |issn=0029-7712}}</ref> On 20 September, he scored twice in a 2–1 away win over West Bromwich Albion in the [[2017–18 EFL Cup#Third round|third-round match]] of the [[2017–18 EFL Cup|League Cup]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41249726 |title=West Bromwich Albion 1–2 Manchester City |date=20 September 2017 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=1 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501053757/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41249726 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 23 September, he scored in a 5–0 win over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41290318 |title=Manchester City 5–0 Crystal Palace |date=23 September 2017 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=8 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210608012102/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41290318 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 14 October, he scored in a 7–2 win over [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41534300 |title=Manchester City 7–2 Stoke City |date=14 October 2017 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=28 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628131642/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41534300 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 21 October, he scored in a 3–0 win over [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-10-20 |title=Manchester City 3-0 Burnley |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41618798 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-10-20 |title=Manchester City 3-0 Burnley |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41618798 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 28 October, he scored in a 3–2 away win over [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41703865 |title=West Bromwich Albion 2–3 Manchester City |date=28 October 2017 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=15 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415023450/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41703865 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=West Brom v Man City, 2017/18 {{!}} Premier League |url=https://www.premierleague.com/match/22441 |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=www.premierleague.com |language=en}}</ref> After scoring and assisting once in each of his three matches, he earned the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] award for October 2017.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/512728 |title=Sane wins EA SPORTS Player of the Month award |access-date=19 December 2017 |archive-date=5 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505191737/https://www.premierleague.com/news/512728 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 6 January 2018, he scored in a 4–1 win in the [[2017–18 FA Cup|FA Cup]] [[2017–18 FA Cup#Third round proper|third round]] over Burnley.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-01-05 |title=Manchester City 4-1 Burnley |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42519596 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Man City 4-1 Burnley (6 Jan, 2018) Final Score - ESPN (UK) |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/499319/burnley-manchester-city |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> On 14 January, he scored in a 4–3 defeat to Liverpool.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-01-12 |title=Liverpool 4-3 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42594403 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Liverpool 4-3 Man City (14 Jan, 2018) Final Score - ESPN (UK) |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/480681/manchester-city-liverpool |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> Nine days later, on 23 January, he scored in a 3–2 away win over Bristol City, securing advancement into the [[2018 EFL Cup Final|League Cup final]], in which he played 77 minutes before being substituted off as City won 3–0 over Arsenal to clinch their first trophy under [[Pep Guardiola]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42698924 |title=Bristol City 2–3 Manchester City (Agg: 3–5) |year=2018 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=5 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605164222/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42698924 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43101681 |title=Arsenal 0–3 Manchester City |date=25 February 2018 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=1 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401043826/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43101681 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 March, five days following the win in the final, he scored against Arsenal in a 3–0 league away win.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43150331 |title=Arsenal 0–3 Manchester City |date=2 March 2018 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=9 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210709214856/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43150331 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 31 March, he scored in a 3–1 away win over Everton, putting City just a win away from winning the league title.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43524315 |title=Everton 1–3 Manchester City |date=31 March 2018 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=17 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817140701/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43524315 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 29 April, he scored in a 4–1 away win over West Ham United.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-04-27 |title=West Ham United 1-4 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43854105 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Sané was voted the [[PFA Young Player of the Year]] for his part in Manchester City's [[2017–18 Premier League]] title win, edging teammates [[Raheem Sterling]] and [[Ederson Moraes|Ederson]], as well as Tottenham Hotspur's [[Harry Kane]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Potts |first=Michael |date=2018-04-22 |title=PFA Young Player of the Year: Full shortlist ahead of tonight's awards |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/949689/PFA-Young-Player-of-the-Year-shortlist-awards-sportgalleries |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=Express.co.uk |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-04-22 |title=Sane named PFA Young Player of the Year |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37551949/manchester-city-leroy-sane-named-pfa-young-player-year |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-04-22 |title=Mohamed Salah: Liverpool forward voted PFA Player of the Year 2017-18 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43860354 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> With [[2017–18 Premier League#Most assists|15 assists]], Sané just missed out on winning the inaugural [[Premier League Playmaker of the Season]] award to teammate [[Kevin De Bruyne]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=De Bruyne edges Playmaker award |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/690283 |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=www.premierleague.com |date=14 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

On 15 September 2018, Sané scored the opening goal and his first of the [[2018–19 Manchester City F.C. season|2018–19 season]] in City's 3–0 home win against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-09-14 |title=Manchester City 3-0 Fulham: Champions ease to victory to maintain unbeaten start |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45456654 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Glendenning |first=Barry |date=2018-09-15 |title=Newcastle 1-2 Arsenal, Manchester City 3-0 Fulham: clockwatch – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2018/sep/15/newcastle-v-arsenal-manchester-city-v-fulham-clockwatch-live |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=the Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He later scored the final goal in consecutive home match wins over Burnley and Southampton.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45847417|title=Manchester City 5–0 Burnley|website=BBC Sport|date=20 October 2018|access-date=29 November 2018|archive-date=17 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200717034327/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45847417|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-11-02 |title=Man City 6-1 Southampton: Blues cruise to comfortable win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46007194 |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 24 November, Sané assisted a first-half goal for Sterling and scored a brace in a 4–0 away win over West Ham United.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45456654|title=West Ham 0–4 Manchester City|website=BBC Sport|date=15 September 2018|access-date=29 November 2018|archive-date=6 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201006045725/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45456654/|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 3 January 2019, he scored the winning goal for Manchester City in the 72nd minute of the game against Liverpool, which resulted in Liverpool's first and only league defeat of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/man-city-liverpool-result-match-report-sergio-aguero-goal-a8710436.html|title=Leroy Sane's pinpoint finish ends Liverpool's unbeaten run to reignite title race|date=3 January 2019|website=The Independent|access-date=5 January 2019|archive-date=9 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201009153011/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/man-city-liverpool-result-match-report-sergio-aguero-goal-a8710436.html|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 February 2019, Manchester City were 2–1 down in the first leg of the [[2018–19 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] [[2018–19 UEFA Champions League knockout phase#Round of 16|round of 16]] tie against Sané's former club, Schalke, playing with only 10 men after [[Nicolás Otamendi]] was sent off on the 68th minute. Sané levelled the scores with a stunning free kick from just under 30 yards only seven minutes after being substituted for [[Sergio Agüero]]. He chose not to celebrate out of respect for his former club. City went on to win the game 3–2 with the winning goal scored by Raheem Sterling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/schalke-vs-man-city-result-final-score-goals-highlights-champions-league-leroy-sane-a8789381.html|title=Sane spurs City to thrilling comeback against Schalke|date=20 February 2019|website=The Independent|access-date=13 March 2019|archive-date=14 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200914002052/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/schalke-vs-man-city-result-final-score-goals-highlights-champions-league-leroy-sane-a8789381.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 13 March 2019, in the second leg of the Champions League round of 16 clash against Schalke, Sané put in an incredible performance with three assists and a goal to contribute to Manchester City's 7–0 victory against his former club, sending City to the quarter-finals of the competition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/03/12/manchester-city-vs-schalke-champions-league-last-16-second-leg/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220112/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/03/12/manchester-city-vs-schalke-champions-league-last-16-second-leg/ |archive-date=12 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Demolition men: Sergio Aguero leads the way as Man City crush Schalke to reach Champions League last eight|last1=Wallace|first1=Sam|date=12 March 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=13 March 2019|last2=Bull|first2=J. J.|issn=0307-1235}}{{cbignore}}</ref> On 24 April 2019, Sané scored the second and final goal in a match against Manchester United during the 66th minute to secure City a Manchester derby win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=513537|title=Manchester United vs. Manchester City – Football Match Report – April 24, 2019|publisher=ESPN|access-date=25 April 2019|archive-date=6 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201006045755/https://www.espn.com/soccer/scoreboard/|url-status=live}}</ref> It was his first Manchester derby goal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=75435&season_id=149|title=Leroy Sane {{!}} Football Stats {{!}} Manchester City {{!}} Season 2016/2017 {{!}} Soccer Base|website=www.soccerbase.com|access-date=25 April 2019|archive-date=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130125934/https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=75435|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=75435&season_id=150|title=Leroy Sane {{!}} Football Stats {{!}} Manchester City {{!}} Season 2017/2018 {{!}} Soccer Base|website=www.soccerbase.com|access-date=25 April 2019|archive-date=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130125934/https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=75435|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=75435&season_id=151|title=Leroy Sane {{!}} Football Stats {{!}} Manchester City {{!}} Season 2018/2019 {{!}} Soccer Base|website=www.soccerbase.com|access-date=25 April 2019|archive-date=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130125934/https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=75435|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2019–20: Injury====
Sané was repeatedly linked with Bundesliga champions [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] to replace club staples [[Franck Ribéry]], who was leaving the club, and retiring [[Arjen Robben]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bavarianfootballworks.com/2019/8/5/20755054/france-football-states-that-leroy-sane-will-join-bayern-munich-for-110-million|title=France Football states that Leroy Sané will join Bayern for €110 million – Bavarian Football Works|last=Football|first=France|date=5 August 2019|work=Bavarian Football Works|access-date=5 August 2019|archive-date=6 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201006045802/https://www.bavarianfootballworks.com/2019/8/5/20755054/france-football-states-that-leroy-sane-will-join-bayern-munich-for-110-million/|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite a deal to the German side reportedly being nearly finalized, Sané was named in the starting 11 against Liverpool in the [[2019 FA Community Shield|FA Community Shield]]. After only 10 minutes, Sané was substituted after sustaining a torn ACL, ruling him out for the majority of the season and ending talks with Bayern until his injury healed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-city-leroy-sane-injury-18067132#:~:text=Sane%20tore%20his%20anterior%20cruciate,time%20after%20such%20an%20injury.|title=Man City star Leroy Sane gives injury update|website=Manchester Evening News|date=9 April 2020|access-date=30 June 2020|archive-date=6 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201006045805/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-city-leroy-sane-injury-18067132#:~:text=Sane%20tore%20his%20anterior%20cruciate,time%20after%20such%20an%20injury.|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2020, Sané rejected a contract extension at Manchester City, with Guardiola stating that Sané would leave the club in the summer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/12010380/leroy-sane-to-leave-manchester-city-says-pep-guardiola|title=Leroy Sane to leave Manchester City, says Pep Guardiola|access-date=19 June 2020|archive-date=6 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201006045807/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/12010380/leroy-sane-to-leave-manchester-city-says-pep-guardiola/|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Bayern Munich===
[[File:2022-07-30 Fußball, Männer, DFL-Supercup, RB Leipzig - FC Bayern München 1DX 3364 by Stepro.jpg|thumb|Sané with [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in 2022]]
On 3 July 2020, Bayern Munich agreed to sign a five-year deal with Sané<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2020/07/leroy-sane-signs-for-fc-bayern-munich-on-five-year-contract|title=Leroy Sané signs for FC Bayern|website=FC Bayern Munich|date=3 July 2020|access-date=5 July 2020|archive-date=1 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201001052839/https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2020/07/leroy-sane-signs-for-fc-bayern-munich-on-five-year-contract|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/leroy-sane-joins-bayern-munich-63729354|title=Leroy Sane joins Bayern Munich|website=mancity.com|date=3 July 2020|access-date=5 July 2020|archive-date=6 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201006045815/https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/leroy-sane-joins-bayern-munich-63729354/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=sport |first1=Guardian |last2=Media |first2=P. A. |date=2020-07-03 |title=Leroy Sané completes move to Bayern Munich from Manchester City |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/jul/03/transfer-news-leroy-sane-joins-bayern-munich-from-manchester-city |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> for an initial €45 million with add-ons rising to a potential €60 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/jun/30/bayern-munich-strike-deal-to-sign-leroy-sane-from-manchester-city-for-41m|title=Bayern Munich strike deal to sign Leroy Sané from Manchester City for £41m|website=The Guardian|date=30 June 2020|access-date=30 June 2020|archive-date=6 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201006045820/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/jun/30/bayern-munich-strike-deal-to-sign-leroy-sane-from-manchester-city-for-41m/|url-status=live}}</ref> Sané scored on his second Bundesliga debut in an 8–0 win against former club Schalke 04.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.kicker.de/bayern-gegen-schalke-2020-bundesliga-4667048/ticker | title = Bayern München – FC Schalke 04 8:0 | language = de | website = [[Kicker (magazine)|Kicker]] | date = 18 September 2020 | access-date = 18 September 2020 | archive-date = 6 October 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20201006045834/https://www.kicker.de/4667048/ticker/fc-bayern-muenchen/fc-schalke-04/ | url-status = live }}</ref> On 3 November 2020, Sané scored his first Champions League goal for Bayern Munich in a 6–2 away win over [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] in the [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League|2020–21 season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/match/2029415--salzburg-vs-bayern/ |title=Salzburg 2–6 Bayern |website=UEFA |date=3 November 2020 |access-date=4 November 2020 |archive-date=21 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211021182158/https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/match/2029415--salzburg-vs-bayern/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|2021–22 Champions League]] season, he scored six goals and provided six assists in ten matches including three goals in two matches against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2021/11/goal-and-assist-sane-continues-champions-league-streak |title=Goal and assist: Sané continues Champions League streak |website=FC Bayern Munich |date=2 November 2021 |access-date=7 September 2022 |archive-date=7 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220907215114/https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2021/11/goal-and-assist-sane-continues-champions-league-streak |url-status=live }}</ref> On 7 September 2022, he scored a goal and had his shot deflected to an own goal in a 2–0 away win against [[Inter Milan]], to be awarded Player of the Match in the first encounter of the [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/champions-league/2022-2023/inter-v-bayern-munich-follow-live_sto9126331/story.shtml |title=Leroy Sané scores brilliant brace as Bayern Munich beat Inter Milan in Champions League opener |website=eurosport.com |date=7 September 2022 |access-date=7 September 2022 |archive-date=14 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230414054633/https://www.eurosport.com/geoblocking.shtml |url-status=live }}</ref> A month later, on 4 October, he scored a brace in a 5–0 win over [[FC Viktoria Plzeň|Viktoria Plzeň]], to reach his 20th goal in the Champions League.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/manuelveth/2022/10/04/leroy-san-stars-in-bayern-munichs-historic-5-0-victory-over-plzen/?sh=2fac8d8c1136 |title=Leroy Sané Stars In Bayern Munich's Historic 5-0 Victory Over Plzen |website=Forbes |date=4 October 2022 |access-date=5 October 2022 |archive-date=5 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221005004020/https://www.forbes.com/sites/manuelveth/2022/10/04/leroy-san-stars-in-bayern-munichs-historic-5-0-victory-over-plzen/?sh=2fac8d8c1136 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 20 September 2023, Sané scored the first goal in a 4–3 victory over Manchester United to be named Man of the Match in the opening fixture of the [[2023–24 UEFA Champions League|2023–24 Champions League]] campaign,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/matches/profis/champions-league/2023-2024/fc-bayern-muenchen-manchester-united-20-09-2023/report |title=Bayern kick off Champions League with Manchester United win |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=20 September 2023 }}</ref> which was also his club's first goal in the competition for the second consecutive season against the same goalkeeper, [[André Onana]], with two different clubs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2023/09/bayern-extend-impressive-champions-league-record-streak-with-opening-win-against-man-utd |title=Bayern extend impressive Champions League record streaks |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=20 September 2023 }}</ref> Subsequently, he was named Bayern's Player of the Month for the previous month of August.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2023/09/leroy-sane-named-bayern-player-of-the-month-for-august-2023 |title=Leroy Sane named Bayern Player of the Month for August 2023 |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=20 September 2023 }}</ref>

===Galatasaray===
In a statement released on 11 June 2025, [[Süper Lig]] club [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] announced that they had reached an agreement with Sané, who was set to arrive in Istanbul to sign an official contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leroy Aziz Sané'nin transferi konusunda görüşmelere başlandı |url=https://www.galatasaray.org/haber/gs-sportif-a-s/leroy-aziz-sane-nin-transferi-konusunda-gorusmelere-baslandi/57938 |website=www.galatasaray.org |publisher=Galatasaray.org |access-date=11 June 2025 |language=tr}}</ref> The following day, Sané signed a three-year deal with the club.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-06-12 |title=Leroy Sané Galatasaray'da! |url=https://www.galatasaray.org/haber/gs-sportif-a-s/leroy-sane-galatasarayda/57945 |access-date=2025-06-12 |publisher=[[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray S.K.]] |language=tr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-06-12 |title=Leroy Sane: Galatasaray set to sign Bayern Munich and Germany winger |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cx2734y53lzo |access-date=2025-06-12 |publisher=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> It was also confirmed that he would wear the number 10 jersey previously worn by [[Dries Mertens]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Leroy Sané'nin imza töreni sonrası ilk açıklamalar |url=https://www.galatasaray.org/haber/gs-sportif-a-s/leroy-sane-nin-imza-toreni-sonrasi-ilk-aciklamalar/57946 |website=www.galatasaray.org |publisher=Galatasaray.org |access-date=12 June 2025 |language=tr}}</ref> Later that year, on 24 August, he scored his first goal for the club in a 4–0 away victory over [[Kayserispor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sport.sky.de/fussball/artikel/erstes-tor-fuer-gala-leroy-sane-macht-den-deckel-drauf/13418001/35311 |title=Erstes Tor für Gala: Leroy Sane macht den Deckel drauf |publisher=Sky Sport |language=de |date=25 August 2025 }}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
[[File:2019-06-11 Fußball, Männer, Länderspiel, Deutschland-Estland StP 2068 LR10 by Stepro.jpg|thumb|Sané with [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in 2019]]

Sané was first called up to the [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany under-21 team]] by youth coach [[Horst Hrubesch]] on 28 August 2015 for the friendly against Denmark and for the [[2017 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] qualifier against [[Azerbaijan national under-21 football team|Azerbaijan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kicker.de/brandt-26-co-_hrubesch-holt-17-neue-633965/artikel |title=Brandt & Co.: Hrubesch holt 17 Neue |work=kicker online |publisher=Olympia Verlag GmbH |date=28 August 2015 |access-date=22 November 2015 |language=de |archive-date=17 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217202507/http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/u21/startseite/633965/artikel_brandt-26-co-_hrubesch-holt-17-neue.html#omsearchresult |url-status=live }}</ref> On 3 September 2015, he made his debut for the German U21 side in a 2–1 win at [[Stadion an der Lohmühle]] in [[Lübeck]] against [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Denmark]], where he was replaced after 73 minutes by [[Julian Brandt]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kicker.de/deutschland-gegen-daenemark-2015-u-nationalteams-freundschaftsspiele-2839788/analyse |title=Sieg trotz Rückstand: DFB-Elf zeigt Moral |work=kicker online |publisher=Olympia Verlag GmbH |date=3 September 2015 |access-date=22 November 2015 |language=de |archive-date=14 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914165534/http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/intligen/intwettbewerbe/u-21-nationalteams-freundschaftsspiele/2015/1/2839788/spielanalyse_deutschland-3096_daenemark-u-21.html#omsearchresult |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Senior===
Sané received his first senior call-up to the [[Germany national football team|German senior team]] on 6 November 2015 in a friendly against [[France national football team|France]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dw.com/en/gomez-returns-trapp-and-san%C3%A9-selected/a-18833110 |title=Gomez returns, Trapp and Sané selected |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=6 November 2015 |access-date=12 November 2015 |archive-date=28 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928113617/https://www.dw.com/en/gomez-returns-trapp-and-san%C3%A9-selected/a-18833110 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sané was eligible to play for France, due to also holding [[French nationality law|French citizenship]].<ref name=":1">{{cite web | url = https://www.aol.co.uk/sport/2016/08/02/5-things-you-need-to-know-about-manchester-city-target-leroy-sane/ | title = 5 things you need to know about Manchester City target Leroy Sane | website = aol.co.uk | date = 2 August 2016 | access-date = 9 November 2020 | archive-date = 9 November 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20201109072246/https://www.aol.co.uk/sport/2016/08/02/5-things-you-need-to-know-about-manchester-city-target-leroy-sane/}}</ref> On 13 November 2015, he was substituted in the 61st-minute for [[Julian Draxler]] in a friendly match against France in [[Stade de France|Saint-Denis]] in a 2–0 defeat for the Germans that was overshadowed by [[November 2015 Paris attacks|shootings and explosions around the stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kicker.de/frankreich-gegen-deutschland-2015-nationalteams-freundschaftsspiele-2856069/spielbericht |title=Frankreichs Sieg verkommt zur Fußnote |work=kicker online |publisher=Olympia Verlag GmbH |date=13 November 2015 |access-date=22 November 2015 |language=de |archive-date=8 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308034630/http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/nationalelf/startseite/fussball-nationalteams-freundschaftsspiele/2015/6/2856069/spielbericht_frankreich_deutschland.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Sané was selected by Germany boss [[Joachim Löw]] to represent the country at [[UEFA Euro 2016]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-finals/season=2016/teams/team=47/squad/index.html |title=UEFA EURO 2016 – Germany – Squad |publisher=UEFA |access-date=6 December 2016 |archive-date=19 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119080541/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-finals/season=2016/teams/team=47/squad/index.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> He participated in one match, replacing [[Bastian Schweinsteiger]] in the 79th minute in Germany's 2–0 semi-final defeat to France.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36669829 |title=Germany 0–2 France |work=BBC Sport |date=7 July 2016 |access-date=6 December 2016 |archive-date=12 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112222813/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36669829 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Sané was omitted from Germany's final 23-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in favour of another young player, Julian Brandt, on 4 June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/germany-announce-final-world-cup-squad-with-manuel-neuer-without-leroy-san%C3%A9/a-44064011 |title=Germany announce final World Cup squad, with Manuel Neuer, without Leroy Sané |publisher=Deutsche Welle |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-date=9 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809080555/https://www.dw.com/en/germany-announce-final-world-cup-squad-with-manuel-neuer-without-leroy-san%C3%A9/a-44064011 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2018, after he was selected for the squad to face games against France and [[Peru national football team|Peru]], he left the team hotel after a discussion with Joachim Löw, citing "personal reasons" as his cause for leaving.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45452552 |title=Leroy Sane: Man City winger leaves Germany team hotel after talks with Joachim Low |date=7 September 2018 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=7 September 2018 |archive-date=9 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909121103/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45452552 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was later revealed that the reason for leaving was due to the birth of his daughter.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45452552 |title=Leroy Sane: Man City winger announces birth of daughter after leaving Germany team hotel |date=8 September 2018 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=8 September 2018 |archive-date=9 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909121103/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45452552 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=LeroySane19|last=Sané|first=Leroy|number=1038393386821210112|title=Incredibly happy to let you know about the birth of my daughter last night  Mother and child are doing fine. |access-date=8 September 2018}}</ref>

On 16 November 2018, he scored his first goal for Germany against [[Russia national football team|Russia]] following an assist from [[Serge Gnabry]]. The goal came in the eighth minute of the game as Germany won 3–0.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.goal.com/en-ar/news/18722/main/2018/11/16/49389132/germany-3-russia-0-sane-on-target-as-lows-men-stroll | title = Germany 3 Russia 0: Sane on target as Low's men stroll | website = goal.com | date = 16 November 2018 | access-date = 3 January 2021 | first = Stephen | last = Creek | archive-date = 18 November 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181118164728/https://www.goal.com/en-ar/news/18722/main/2018/11/16/49389132/germany-3-russia-0-sane-on-target-as-lows-men-stroll | url-status = live }}</ref>

On 19 May 2021, he was selected to the squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kicker.de/em-kader-offiziell-loew-beruft-mueller-hummels-und-volland-804642/artikel|title=EM-Kader offiziell: Löw beruft Müller, Hummels und Volland|date=19 May 2021|website=[[Kicker (magazine)|Kicker]]|language=de|access-date=19 May 2021|archive-date=7 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210607123628/https://www.kicker.de/em-kader-offiziell-loew-beruft-mueller-hummels-und-volland-804642/artikel|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Das |first=Andrew |date=2021-05-18 |title=Euro 2020 Rosters: Who Made the Cut? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/05/18/sports/soccer/uefa-euro-2020-rosters.html |access-date=2025-03-30 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He played in all four of Germany's matches: starting once against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/19692/12340079/germany-2-2-hungary-leon-goretzkas-late-equaliser-sees-germany-survive-euro-2020-scare|title=Germany 2-2 Hungary: Leon Goretzka's late equaliser sees Germany survive Euro 2020 scare|date=21 June 2021|access-date=13 January 2024|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> and appearing as a substitute against [[France national football team|France]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51197804|title=France 1-0 Germany: Mats Hummels own goal sees Euro 2020 favourites France beat Germany|date=15 June 2024|access-date=13 January 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/portugal-germany-live-line-ups-stats-uea-euro-2020-cristiano-ronaldo-havertz-16274|title=Four-goal Germany run riot to see off Cristiano Ronaldo and Portugal|date=19 June 2021|access-date=13 January 2024|website=Bundesliga}}</ref> and [[England national football team|England]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-06-30/euro-2020-england-beats-germany-sterling-kane/100251876|title=England beats Germany 2-0 at Euro 2020, Raheem Sterling and Harry Kane get the goals|date=29 June 2021|access-date=13 January 2024|website=ABC}}</ref>

In November 2022, he was named in the 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/flick-beruft-moukoko-fuellkrug-und-goetze-in-wm-kader-245974/ |title=Flick beruft Moukoko, Füllkrug und Götze in WM-Kader |trans-title=Flick names Moukoko, Füllkrug and Götze to World Cup squad |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=10 November 2022 |access-date=10 November 2022 |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-10-25 |title=Who makes Germany's provisional World Cup squad? - Get German Football News |url=https://www.getfootballnewsgermany.com/2022/who-makes-germanys-provisional-world-cup-squad/ |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=www.getfootballnewsgermany.com |language=en-US}}</ref>

In June 2024, Sané was named in Germany's squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://olympics.com/en/news/uefa-euro-2024-all-squads-and-players-full-list|title=UEFA Euro 2024: All squads and players full list|date=7 June 2024|access-date=7 June 2024|website=Olympics.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Julian Nagelsmann confirms Germany's Euro 2024 squad |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/germany-squad-euro-2024-nagelsmann-27361 |access-date=2025-03-30 |website=www.bundesliga.com |language=en}}</ref>

On 21 May 2026, he was selected in Germany’s 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dfb.de/news/bundestrainer-nagelsmann-gibt-wm-kader-bekannt|title=Bundestrainer Nagelsmann gibt WM-Kader bekannt|publisher=[[German Football Association]]|language=de|date=21 May 2026|access-date=21 May 2026}}</ref>

